MapSales Review: 2008 to 2017

City of Toronto

April 20, 2018

1.0 Introduction

The City of Toronto provides access to geospatial data through a number of different services. Foundational data, consisting of address, centreline (i.e.streets), parcels, topographic (i.e.buildings, catchbasin, tree, etc.), aerial photography and elevation (i.e.LiDAR), can be obtained from two sources; the Citys Open Data Portal and through the MapSales service.

The current version of the Open Data portal does not allow for data to be downloaded in different file formats, geographic projections, as a subset, or in a custom tiling schema. For this reason the MapSales service was established to provide a more custom data delivery service. MapSales is available to the general public, businesses, consultants, educational organizations, and City of Toronto employees. In cases where City of Toronto employees request data for internal uses, or to provide to consultants who are working on a City of Toronto project all fees are waived, otherwise MapSales operates on a cost recovery fee based system, as defined by City Council.

The City of Toronto has a direction to improve customer service, improve operational efficiencies, and align to the Internation Open Data charter,which is open by default. In order to meet these goals the Geospatial Competency Centre is reviewing the MapDesk service to better understand areas for improvement and operational efficiencies.

2.0 Prerequists

Performing analysis in RStudios requires various packages and source data. For this analysis four packages will be utilized; tidyverse, stringr, lubridate, and googlesheets.

3.0 Cleaning Source Data

Data quality is important for analytics and data cleaning is required in most data analytics projects. MapSales was developed in the early 2000s and has experienced numerous changes over the past decade and a half, resulting in changes to data entry. These changes resulted in variations causing difficulties when analyzing variables over a period of time. Data cleaning removes errors and standardizes values, improving analysis techniques.

3.1 Explore Column Attributes

MapSales records many different types of information related to requests, many of which has changed over the years, specifically division names, products and formats. City division names have changed over the ten year period, new products have been created, and data formats have been added. In order to perform meaningful analysis, the distinct attribute values must be understood to identify areas that may require data cleaning and standardization.

# Explore data categories for discripencies, duplication, and errors prior to cleaning

# Review distinct division names
mapSales %>%
  distinct(DIVISION) %>%
  arrange(DIVISION)
## Warning: package 'bindrcpp' was built under R version 3.4.4
# Review distinct product names
mapSales %>%
  distinct(PRODUCTNAME_1) %>%
  arrange(PRODUCTNAME_1)
# Review distinct format types
mapSales %>%
  distinct(FORMAT) %>%
  arrange(FORMAT)

3.5 Clean and Order Data

The final data cleaning was to make the data more readable and usable for additional analysis.

# Rename column names
cleanData <- rename(cleanData, OrderID = 'ORDERID', OrderDate = 'ORDERDATE_YYYYMMDD', Description = 'DESCRIPTION', PaymentID = 'PAYMENTID', PaymentMethod = 'PAYMENTMETHOD', DivUnitID = 'DIVUNITID', Division = 'DIVISION', Unit = 'UNIT', School = 'SCHOOL', ProductDetailID = 'PRODUCTDETAILID', ProductID = 'PRODUCTNAME', ProductType = 'PRODUCTNAME_1', Format = 'FORMAT', Quantity = 'QUANTITY', CostingType = 'COSTINGTYPE', TotalCost = 'TOTALPRICE')

# Create year and month column
cleanData$OrderYear <- year(ymd(cleanData$OrderDate))
cleanData$OrderMonth <- month(ymd(cleanData$OrderDate))

# Add new empty columns
cleanData$DivClass <- NA
cleanData$ProductClass <- NA
cleanData$FormatClass <- NA

head(cleanData)
# Convert integer to string to date

cleanData$OrderYear <- year(ymd(cleanData$OrderDate))
cleanData$OrderMonth <- month(ymd(cleanData$OrderDate))

head(cleanData)

3.6 Export to CSV

The cleaned MapSales data was exported to a CSV so that it could be added into a Googlesheet, as the Googlesheet API has a limitation on how much data can be written at a single time. As this dataset has ~13,000 records, writing to a Googlesheet directly was not feasible.

# Save cleanData to csv

cleanMapSales <- write_csv(cleanData, "C:/WorkDocs/Analysis/MapSales/cleanMapSales.csv")
